{"key":"post-8891058","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8891058</id>\n<content>The first thing you need to do is separate them from those wet rocks.&amp;nbsp; They're trying to colonize them and that inhibits fruiting.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Second, when they pin on the bottom only, it indicates low humidity and/or dry cakes.&amp;nbsp; Since they want to pin in 100% humidity, right close to the damp rocks is the only place they're finding the right conditions.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Get some foil or something larger than you have to separate them from what's below.&amp;nbsp; Mist more often, and soak the cakes in water for 24 hours after the flush.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I'd suggest getting rid of the hydroton and replacing it with damp, well drained perlite.&amp;nbsp; Perlite has about 1000 times the surface area and will provide far better humidification.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8891071</next>\n<prev>8891042</prev>\n<first>8890767</first>\n<last>8904681</last>\n<when>1220817414</when>\n<utime>09/07/08 10:56 PM</utime>\n</post>"}